{"title_page": "Mughal\u2013Persian Wars", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Mughal\u2013Persian Wars\n| image       = Nadir Shah at the sack of Delhi - Battle scene with Nader Shah on horseback, possibly by Muhammad Ali ibn Abd al-Bayg ign Ali Quli Jabbadar, mid-18th century, Museum of Fine Arts, Boston.jpg\n| image_size  = 230px\n| caption     = Representation of [[Nader Shah]] at the sack of [[Delhi]]\n| partof      = \n| place       = [[Afghanistan]], [[India]]\n| result      = * [[Old Kandahar|Kandahar]] falls to [[Mughals]] in 1595\n* [[Savafids]] captured Kandahar in 1623\n* Mughals reconquered Kandahar in 1638\n* Safavids again captured Kandahar in 1649\n* In 1739, Afsharids invaded India and [[sack of Delhi|sacked Delhi]]\n| territory   = Persians briefly occupy as far as Delhi\n| combatant1  = [[Iran]]<br>\n* [[File:Safavid Flag.svg|25px|border]] [[Safavid dynasty]]\n* [[File:Nadir Shah Flag.svg|border|25px]] [[Afsharid dynasty]]\n| combatant2  = [[File:Alam of the Mughal Empire.svg|25px]][[Mughal Empire]]\n| commander1  = [[Abbas I of Persia]]<br>[[Abbas II of Persia]]<br>Mehr\u0101 Khan<br>Autar Khan<br>[[Nader Shah]]<br>[[Heraclius II of Georgia]]\n| commander2  = [[Jahangir]]<br>Kilij Khan<br>[[Murad Baksh]]<br>[[Dara Shikoh]]<br>[[Aurangzeb]]<br>[[Muhammad Shah]]\n| strength1   = Appx. 50,000 in 1623<br>62,000 in 1649<br>55,000 in 1739<ref>Floor, Wiilem(2009). ''The rise & fall of Nader Shah: Dutch East India Company Reports 1730\u20131747'', Mage Publishers</ref><ref>Floor, Willem(1998). ''new facts on Nadir Shah's campaign in India'' in Iranian studies, p.198-219</ref><ref name=\"Jaques 2006 512\">{{Citation | last = Jaques | first = Tony | contribution = Karnal-1739-Nader Shah#Invasion of India | year = 2006 | title = Dictionary of Battles and Sieges: A Guide to 8,500 Battles from Antiquity through the Twenty-first Century | pages = 512 | place = Westport, CT | publisher = Greenwood }}</ref><br>\n| strength2   = 3000 in 1623<br>98,000 in 1638<br>2000 in 1649\n| casualties1 = ~7500\n| casualties2 = ~27,000\n}}\n\nThe '''Mughal\u2013Persian Wars''' were a series of wars fought in the 17th and 18th centuries between the [[Safavid Empire|Safavid]] and [[Afsharid Empire]]s of Persia, and the [[Mughal Empire]], over what is now Afghanistan. The Mughals consolidated their control of what is today India and Pakistan in the 16th century, and gradually came into conflict with the powerful Safavids and Afsharids, led by [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]] and [[Nader Shah]] respectively. Aside from Nader Shah's invasion of the Mughal Empire, most of the conflict between the two powers were limited to battles for control over Kandahar.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d1wUgKKzawoC&pg=PA150 |title=''Advanced Study in the History of Modern India 1707-1813''|accessdate=4 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==War of 1622\u201323==\n{{Main|Mughal\u2013Safavid War (1622\u201323)}} The '''Mughal\u2013Safavid War of 1622\u201323''' was fought over the important fortress city of [[Kandahar]], in [[Afghanistan]], between the Safavid empire of Persia and the Mughal empire of India. It resulted in a clear [[Safavids|Persian]] victory.\n\n[[File:Muhammad Ali Beg.jpg|thumb|Muhammad Ali Beg was the [[Persia]]n ambassador sent to the Mughal court of [[Jahangir]] by [[Abbas I of Persia]], arriving in time for [[Muharram]] in March 1631. He remained there until October 1632, thus negotiating an end to the conflict between the Mughals and the [[Safavids]].]]\n\nHaving secured crushing victories against the Ottomans, Shah Abbas desired to capture the strategic fortress on Kandahar since he had lost it in 1595.<ref name=\"Burton159\">Burton 1997, p. 159</ref> In 1605 the governor of [[Herat]], [[Hosayn Khan]], besieged the city but the tenacious defense of the Mughal governor, [[Shah Beg Khan]], and the arrival in the next year of a relieving Mughal army to Kandahar forced the Safavids to retreat.<ref name=\"Iranica\">Iranica 2011</ref><ref name=\"Kohn337\">Kohn 2007, p. 337</ref> With the conclusion of the [[Ottoman-Safavid War (1603-1618)]], Shah Abbas was secure enough for a war on his eastern frontier,{{r|Burton159}} so in 1621 he ordered an army to gather at [[Nishapur]].{{r|Burton159}} After celebrating the new year at [[Tabas Gilaki]] in southern [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]], Abbas joined with his army and marched on Kandahar where he arrived on 20 May and immediately began the siege.{{r|Burton159}} Though [[Jahangir]] had information of the Persian's movements he was too slow to respond,{{r|Burton159}} and without reinforcements the small garrison of 3,000 men could not hold for long against the superior Persian army.<ref name=\"Chandra221\">Chandra 2005, p. 221</ref>\n\nThe Emperor asked his son and heir apparent [[Shah Jahan|Khurram]] who was at [[Mandav|Mandu]] in the [[Deccan Plateau|Deccan]] to lead the campaign, but Khurram evaded the assignment fearing to lose his political power while he was away from court.<ref name=\"Chandra242\">Chandra 2005, p. 242</ref> The relief force the Mughals could assemble proved too small to raise the siege,{{r|Kohn337}} so after a 45-day siege the city fell on 22 June followed shortly after by [[Zamindawar]].<ref name=\"Burton160\">Burton 1997, p. 160</ref> After fortifying the city and appointing [[Ganj Ali Khan]] as governor of the city,{{r|Iranica}} Abbas returned to [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]] via [[Gh\u014dr Province|Ghur]], subduing on the way troubling emirs in [[Chaghcharan]] and [[Gharjistan]].<ref name=\"Burton161\">Burton 1997, p. 161</ref> The rebellion of Khurram absorbed the Mughal's attention, so in the spring of 1623 a Mughal envoy arrived at the Shah's camp with a letter from the Emperor accepting the loss of Kandahar and putting an end to the conflict.<ref name=\"Burton162\">Burton 1997, p. 162</ref>\n\n==War of 1638==\n[[File:The Surrender of Kandahar.jpg|thumb|''The Surrender of Kandahar'', a miniature painting from the ''[[Padshahnama]]'' depicting Persians surrendering keys of the city to [[Shah Jahan]] in 1638]]\nIn spring of year 1638, the Mughal Emperor [[Shah Jahan]] himself led the massive Mughal army of around 100,000 troops to reconquer the province of [[Kandahar]]. Accompanied by his sons, the city was completely blockaded as the emperor had targeted a greater campaign for conquering not only the Persian frontiers, but also the conquest of central Asia. Within a month, the Safavid governor surrendered to the Mughal forces and Kandahar was once again became a part of the vast [[Mughal Empire]].<ref name=\"Kinra\">Kinra 2015, p.157</ref> Kandahar in particular was at the crossroads of a number of major commercial trade routes in Central Asia. The two cities were thus the subject of deep strategic concern.<ref name=\"dlx.b-ok.org\">http://dlx.b-ok.org/genesis/628000/06ae9010b197a442876290ce257027ff/_as/</ref>\n\n==War of 1649\u201353==\n{{Main|Mughal\u2013Safavid War (1649\u201353)}}\nThe '''Mughal\u2013Safavid War of 1649-53''' was fought between the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] and [[Safavid Empire|Safavid]] empires in the territory of modern [[Afghanistan]]. The war began after a Persian army, while the Mughals were at war with the [[Khanate of Bukhara|Janid Uzbeks]], captured the fortress city of [[Kandahar]] and other strategic cities that controlled the region. The Mughals attempted unsuccessfully to regain the city from the Persians, thus the war resulted in a Persian victory.\n\n==Nadir Shah's invasion of India==\n{{main|Nader Shah's invasion of the Mughal Empire}}\nAttracted by its wealth and knowing that the victim was much weaker, Emperor [[Nadir Shah]], the [[Shah of Iran]] (1736\u201347) and founder of the [[Afsharid dynasty]], invaded Northern India with a fifty-five thousand strong army, eventually attacking [[Delhi]] in March 1739 where he completely [[sack of Delhi|sacked and looted the city]], after issuing orders for a general massacre to take place.<ref name=Ma200>[[#Ma|Marshman, P. 200]]</ref> His army had defeated the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor [[Muhammad Shah]] at the battle at [[Battle of Karnal|Karnal]] in less than three hours and had taken over control of northern India.<ref name=br>{{cite web |title= Nadir Shah|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/401451/Nadir-Shah |date= |publisher=[[Britannica.com]] }}</ref> The Mughal emperor Muhammad Shah had to beg Nader to grant him and his people mercy, after ceding the keys of the city and royal treasury to him. (Which included the legendary [[Peacock throne]], the symbol of Iranian imperial might, and the fabulous [[Darya-e noor]] and [[Koh-i-noor]]).\n\nThe [[Battle of Karnal]] (13 February 1739), was a decisive victory for [[Nader Shah]], the emperor of the [[Afsharid dynasty]] during his [[Nader Shah's invasion of India|invasion of India]]. The Shah's forces defeated the numerically superior army of [[Muhammad Shah]], the Indian emperor of the Mughal dynasty, in little more than three hours thus paving the way for the Persian [[sack of Delhi]]. The battle took place at [[Karnal]], {{convert|110|km|mi}} north of [[Delhi]], [[India]].\n\n==References and notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Safavids}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mughal-Persian Wars}}\n[[Category:Wars involving the Safavid Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Mughal\u2013Persian Wars\n| image       = Nadir Shah at the sack of Delhi - Battle scene with Nader Shah on horseback, possibly by Muhammad Ali ibn Abd al-Bayg ign Ali Quli Jabbadar, mid-18th century, Museum of Fine Arts, Boston.jpg\n| image_size  = 230px\n| caption     = Representation of [[Nader Shah]] at the sack of [[Delhi]]\n| partof      = \n| place       = [[Afghanistan]], [[India]]\n| result      = * [[Old Kandahar|Kandahar]] falls to [[Mughals]] in 1595\n* [[Savafids]] captured Kandahar in 1623\n* Mughals reconquered Kandahar in 1638\n* Safavids again captured Kandahar in 1649\n* In 1739, Afsharids invaded India and [[sack of Delhi|sacked Delhi]]\n| territory   = Persians briefly occupy as far as Delhi\n| combatant1  = [[Iran]]<br>\n* [[File:Safavid Flag.svg|25px|border]] [[Safavid dynasty]]\n* [[File:Nadir Shah Flag.svg|border|25px]] [[Afsharid dynasty]]\n| combatant2  = [[File:Alam of the Mughal Empire.svg|25px]][[Mughal Empire]]\n| commander1  = [[Abbas I of Persia]]<br>[[Abbas II of Persia]]<br>Mehr\u0101 Khan<br>Autar Khan<br>[[Nader Shah]]<br>[[Heraclius II of Georgia]]\n| commander2  = [[Jahangir]]<br>Kilij Khan<br>[[Murad Baksh]]<br>[[Dara Shikoh]]<br>[[Aurangzeb]]<br>[[Muhammad Shah]]\n| strength1   = Appx. 50,000 in 1623<br>62,000 in 1649<br>55,000 in 1739<ref>Floor, Wiilem(2009). ''The rise & fall of Nader Shah: Dutch East India Company Reports 1730\u20131747'', Mage Publishers</ref><ref>Floor, Willem(1998). ''new facts on Nadir Shah's campaign in India'' in Iranian studies, p.198-219</ref><ref name=\"Jaques 2006 512\">{{Citation | last = Jaques | first = Tony | contribution = Karnal-1739-Nader Shah#Invasion of India | year = 2006 | title = Dictionary of Battles and Sieges: A Guide to 8,500 Battles from Antiquity through the Twenty-first Century | pages = 512 | place = Westport, CT | publisher = Greenwood }}</ref><br>\n| strength2   = 3000 in 1623<br>98,000 in 1638<br>2000 in 1649\n| casualties1 = ~7500\n| casualties2 = ~27,000\n}}\n\nThe '''Mughal\u2013Persian Wars''' were a series of wars fought in the 17th and 18th centuries between the [[Safavid Empire|Safavid]] and [[Afsharid Empire]]s of Persia, and the [[Mughal Empire]], over what is now Afghanistan. The Mughals consolidated their control of what is today India and Pakistan in the 16th century, and gradually came into conflict with the powerful Safavids and Afsharids, led by [[Abbas I]] and [[Nader Shah]] respectively. Aside from Nader Shah's invasion of the Mughal Empire, most of the conflict between the two powers were limited to battles for control over Kandahar.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d1wUgKKzawoC&pg=PA150 |title=''Advanced Study in the History of Modern India 1707-1813''|accessdate=4 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==War of 1622\u201323==\n{{Main|Mughal\u2013Safavid War (1622\u201323)}} The '''Mughal\u2013Safavid War of 1622\u201323''' was fought over the important fortress city of [[Kandahar]], in [[Afghanistan]], between the Safavid empire of Persia and the Mughal empire of India. It resulted in a clear [[Safavids|Persian]] victory.\n\n[[File:Muhammad Ali Beg.jpg|thumb|Muhammad Ali Beg was the [[Persia]]n ambassador sent to the Mughal court of [[Jahangir]] by [[Abbas I of Persia]], arriving in time for [[Muharram]] in March 1631. He remained there until October 1632, thus negotiating an end to the conflict between the Mughals and the [[Safavids]].]]\n\nHaving secured crushing victories against the Ottomans, Shah Abbas desired to capture the strategic fortress on Kandahar since he had lost it in 1595.<ref name=\"Burton159\">Burton 1997, p. 159</ref> In 1605 the governor of [[Herat]], [[Hosayn Khan]], besieged the city but the tenacious defense of the Mughal governor, [[Shah Beg Khan]], and the arrival in the next year of a relieving Mughal army to Kandahar forced the Safavids to retreat.<ref name=\"Iranica\">Iranica 2011</ref><ref name=\"Kohn337\">Kohn 2007, p. 337</ref> With the conclusion of the [[Ottoman-Safavid War (1603-1618)]], Shah Abbas was secure enough for a war on his eastern frontier,{{r|Burton159}} so in 1621 he ordered an army to gather at [[Nishapur]].{{r|Burton159}} After celebrating the new year at [[Tabas Gilaki]] in southern [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]], Abbas joined with his army and marched on Kandahar where he arrived on 20 May and immediately began the siege.{{r|Burton159}} Though [[Jahangir]] had information of the Persian's movements he was too slow to respond,{{r|Burton159}} and without reinforcements the small garrison of 3,000 men