rticular was at the crossroads of a number of major commercial trade routes in Central Asia. The two cities were thus the subject of deep strategic concern.<ref name=\"dlx.b-ok.org\">http://dlx.b-ok.org/genesis/628000/06ae9010b197a442876290ce257027ff/_as/</ref>\n\n==War of 1649\u201353==\n{{Main|Mughal\u2013Safavid War (1649\u201353)}}\nThe '''Mughal\u2013Safavid War of 1649-53''' was fought between the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] and [[Safavid Empire|Safavid]] empires in the territory of modern [[Afghanistan]]. The war began after a Persian army, while the Mughals were at war with the [[Khanate of Bukhara|Janid Uzbeks]], captured the fortress city of [[Kandahar]] and other strategic cities that controlled the region. The Mughals attempted unsuccessfully to regain the city from the Persians, thus the war resulted in a Persian victory.\n\n==Nadir Shah's invasion of India==\n{{main|Nader Shah's invasion of the Mughal Empire}}\nAttracted by its wealth and knowing that the victim was much weaker, Emperor [[Nadir Shah]], the [[Shah of Iran]] (1736\u201347) and founder of the [[Afsharid dynasty]], invaded Northern India with a fifty-five thousand strong army, eventually attacking [[Delhi]] in March 1739 where he completely [[sack of Delhi|sacked and looted the city]], after issuing orders for a general massacre to take place.<ref name=Ma200>[[#Ma|Marshman, P. 200]]</ref> His army had defeated the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor [[Muhammad Shah]] at the battle at [[Battle of Karnal|Karnal]] in less than three hours and had taken over control of northern India.<ref name=br>{{cite web |title= Nadir Shah|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/401451/Nadir-Shah |date= |publisher=[[Britannica.com]] }}</ref> The Mughal emperor Muhammad Shah had to beg Nader to grant him and his people mercy, after ceding the keys of the city and royal treasury to him. (Which included the legendary [[Peacock throne]], the symbol of Iranian imperial might, and the fabulous [[Darya-e noor]] and [[Koh-i-noor]]).\n\nThe [[Battle of Karnal]] (13 February 1739), was a decisive victory for [[Nader Shah]], the emperor of the [[Afsharid dynasty]] during his [[Nader Shah's invasion of India|invasion of India]]. The Shah's forces defeated the numerically superior army of [[Muhammad Shah]], the Indian emperor of the Mughal dynasty, in little more than three hours thus paving the way for the Persian [[sack of Delhi]]. The battle took place at [[Karnal]], {{convert|110|km|mi}} north of [[Delhi]], [[India]].\n\n==References and notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Safavids}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mughal-Persian Wars}}\n[[Category:Wars involving the Safavid Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAbbas I(link changed toAbbas I of Persia) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mughal%E2%80%93Persian_Wars"}
